Henry Draper Image Collection
Draper, Henry, 1837-1882
MC.230
81 items in 40 boxes
circa 1870s Henry Draper was a physician and dean of faculty of the Medical Department of the University of the City of New York (now New York University). He was also a pioneer in the field of astrophotography. This collection contains many glass plates of his photographs, many of which are astronomical images. Some slides also relate to his research and teaching at the University. Use the language: Materials are stored offsite and advance notice is required for use. Please request materials at least two business days prior to your research visit to coordinate access.
Conditions Governing Access
Repository permission is required for access. Please contact New York University Archives, 212-998-2641, university-archives@nyu.edu.
Immediate Source of Acquisition
Upon Henry Draper's death in 1882 the items in this collection were in his New York laboratory. Draper's sister, Mrs. Antonia Dixon, presented these items to the University. The accession number related to this collection is 82.030.

This finding aid is arranged by subject; however, the collection is housed according to the format's size. The container list provides information on where to locate each object.

Biographical note
Henry Draper was born March 7, 1837, to John William Draper and Antonia Coetana de Paiva Pereira Gardner. John William Draper was a doctor, chemist, and professor at the University of the City of New York (now New York University), and his son Henry followed closely in his footsteps. Henry Draper graduated from the Medical Department of the University of the City of New York in 1857. He became a physician at Bellevue Hospital and later returned to the University as a professor and eventually as dean of faculty of the Medical Department. Despite his employment as a doctor, Draper also spent a large amount of time on his passion of astrophotography. He even built his own observatory on his father's estate at Hastings-on-Hudson. Draper was a pioneer in the astrophotography field, directing an expedition to photograph the 1874 transit of Venus and being the first to photograph an astronomical nebula with his image of the Orion Nebula in 1880. He was also interested in spectra, taking the first image of the stellar spectrum in 1872. Draper also invented the slit spectrograph and improved on many photographic tools such as telescope clock drives which are necessary to steady long photographic exposures.
In 1867 Henry Draper married the wealthy socialite Anna Mary Palmer. Not only was she an able laboratory assistant, but she also helped turn their home into a center for celebrities and scientists. Draper was well recognized, receiving honorary law degrees from the University of the City of New York and the University of Wisconsin, a Congressional medal, and election to both the National Academy of Sciences and the Astronomische Gesellschaft. Unfortunately, Draper became ill during a trip to the Rocky Mountains and died of double pleurisy at the age of 45. His wife established the Henry Draper Memorial that awards the Henry Draper Medal for astrophysics and funded the Henry Draper Catalog, which is a massive photographic stellar spectrum survey.
Source: "Henry Draper," in Biographical Encyclopedia of Astronomers, ed. Thomas Hockey (New York: Springer, 2007).
Physical Characteristics and Technical Requirements
Fragile materials may only be handled with the assistance of an archivist. Digital surrogates may be created for objects too fragile to handle. Please contact New York University Archives with any questions regarding digital surrogates.
Preferred Citation
Identification of item, date; Henry Draper Image Collection; MC 230; box number; folder number or item identifier; Repository Name, New York University.
Processing Information
The titles assigned to each plate primarily derive from titles written on the envelopes in which the items were originally housed. It is unclear who assigned these titles and when he or she did so. Based on the age of the envelopes, this description was likely not in Draper's hand. Some of the items in Series I with names of specific elements are derived from titles on the actual object, and these are more likely to have been written by Draper himself. Untitled items were given the same title as the series in which they are found.
This collection was originally described by T.J. Herczeg (University of Oklahoma's Department of Physics and Astronomy) and Anne Kinney (NYU's Department of Physics) for a 1982 article, "The Collection of Henry Draper Memorabilia in the New York University Archives." However, the arrangement of the collection has been altered since that date.
The glass covers of the daguerreotypes were replaced by the National Museum of American History (NMAH) in 1987. In March 2017, one of the original glass covers was discovered by the NMAH staff. This was returned to the NYU Archives in November 2018 (now housed in box 10).
In 2019, a wooden cabinet that housed glass plate negatives was sent to offsite storage.

Scope and Contents
This collection consists of primarily glass plates of images taken by Draper and the wooden cabinet where negatives were stored. They include astrophotography images of the moon and solar spectra along with images of sites of Draper's work, such as the University campus and his observatory at Hastings-on-Hudson. Some of these glass slides have been damaged and now only exist in partial fragments. Additionally, this collection contains Draper's collection of lantern slides of historical images and reproductions of his photographs used in educational presentations.
